On @realmoney Today's Key Takeaway We can never be sure of the market's future - especially these days! But, frankly, I am increasingly confident that we have reentered a period of rising uncertainty and volatility as discussed in my opening missive,

Buckle Up, More and Heightened Volatility Lies Ahead realmoney.thestreet.com/doug…. Here are some of the possible ingredients to greater stretches of volatility: * The Orange Swan: President Trump forms hastily crafted policy on the back of an envelope delivered by tweets.

The continuation of this sort of policy making and decision delivery - whether one favors it or not politically - is inherently problematic for the markets (which prefer certainty). For a while I have thought that the president's behavior and policies would ultimately impact

the markets - we are now at that point. * The Death of Pax Americana: Our world - in political and economic terms - is increasingly flat and interconnected. So, by trying to abolish the post World War II order, we have entered a trade war without allies. Using unilateral policy

I will continue to ask the question: "In a networked world are we as investors and citizens as safe as the markets assume?" In other words, this is more than about trade - and the markets may be smelling this worrisome development. * The U.S. and China Have Different Time Frames

: As I frequently have stated, the president's tactics employed on trade will not work - leaving us with months and likely years of continued and ineffective trade discussions. Trump thinks in timeframes of a tweet while China thinks in terms of decades and even a century.

* An Extended Trade Quarrel May Hamstring the Federal Reserve: Yes, growth will be threatened but a tariff war could, at the same time, raise inflation and inflationary expectations. Stagflation, anyone? * Markets are Exposed to a Spurt In Valuation in 2019:

Even as we witnessed a swift deceleration in the rate of S&P earnings growth, valuations have expanded by 3-4 price earnings multiple points this year. * Market Participants Have Grown Increasingly Complacent: I measure this on a record level short VIX, a leap in speculative

long positions in S&P futures (and equivalents) and in a high reading, until quite recently, in the CNN Fear & Greed Index. * Seasonal Pressures: The "Sell in May Crowd" has seasonality on its side. * A Changing Market Structure Poses Risks and Presents A Backdrop of More

Volatility: The popularity and proliferation of ETFs, the rising role of quant strategies and CTAs are a potential "trigger" that threaten the steady rise of prices since Christmas Eve if prices continue to breakdown. As I have written, we live in an investment world in which

"buyers live higher and sellers live lower." Antithetical to value investing - there are, unlike the past - providing little ammunition to deflect a move that may soon be running in reverse after the last four bullish months.
* Recent Broken High Profile IPOs Have Soured Investors: Discussed here, in Cheap Fabric and Dim Lighting! realmoney.thestreet.com/doug… @cnbcfastmoney @SquawkCNBC

@realmoney I wrote this when I begun buying $GLD. Now very large... Apr 24, 2019 | 08:41 AM EDT DOUG KASS Gold Goes on My Best Ideas List I am placing (GLD) on my Best Ideas for the reasons mentioned yesterday:

* The repression of interest rates, in the fullness of time, should benefit the price of gold "The Fed may not hike interest rates in my lifetime." - Larry Kudlow $GLD share price has declined from $126.70/share on February 19, 2019 to $120.20 in pre-market trading this morning.

I view this as an intermediate term opportunity and I plan to reestablish my long position in gold SPDR Gold Shares (GLD) today. My investment thesis is simple and self evident: * Central banks seem hell bent in continuing their monetary largesse as signs of a structural growth

slowdown multiply. * Whether it's the ease of current policy, or, in the extreme, a broadening acceptance of modern monetary theory (MMT) - the pendulum of monetary belief seems to have shifted to near perpetual ease. * In the U.S. (from both sides of the political pew) and

around the world, prudent financial discipline has been abandoned - government debt loads are breaking new records and will and can not be paid off given structural economic headwinds. * Debasing of currencies and disregard for sovereign deficits should be viewed as friendly to

the gold markets. * Real interest rates have fallen sharply - which gold historically is tied to. (The five year real rate has fallen from 1.16% in November to only 0.51% today.) Given the above, it seems that a core position in gold makes sense. @jimcramer @tomkeene
